Flight Lieutenant '''Edward Rodolph Clement Scholefield''' 1893-1929 [[Distinguished Conduct Medal|DCM]] [[Air Force Cross (United Kingdom)|AFC]] (known as '''Tiny Scholefield''') was an aviator and a motor racing driver. He was killed during a test flight of a [[Vickers Type 170 Vanguard|Vickers Vanguard]] airliner in 1929.<ref name="obit" />

==Early life==
Scholefield was born on 22 October 1893 in Calgary, Alberta, Canada.<ref name="RAeC" /> In the 1901 Census of Bournemouth Scholefield aged 6 is listed with his sister Vandine as boarders at a School.<ref name="Census1901" />

==Aviator==
Scholefield was awarded a French aviators certificate on 5 April 1912.<ref name="RAeC" /> He joined the Royal Flying Corps as an airmen at the start of the [[First World War]] and was later commissioned.<ref name="obit" /> In 1915 when on patrol over the Western Front he was shot down and taken prisoner, he remained a German [[prisoner of war]] until the end of the war.<ref name="obit" /> During the war he had won the [[Distinguished Conduct Medal]] and following the war he became an experimental test pilot at the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]]. In 1923 he was awarded the [[Air Force Cross (United Kingdom)|Air Force Cross]].<ref name="Gazette32782" />

==Test Pilot==
[[File:Vickers Vanguard 1928.jpg|thumb|right|G-EBCP the Vickers Vanguard in which Scholefield lost his life]]
Following his retirement from the [[Royal Air Force]] Scholefied became Chief Test Pilot for [[Vickers]] and became well known as an air racer and demonstration pilot.<ref name="obit" />  It was not usual in the 1920s for pilots to wear parachutes but he was given one in June 1926 to use, with an instruction that it was to be used on all test flights. The following day he found himself in trouble when he had inverted an aircraft (a [[Vickers Wibault]]) and it would not right itself, he used the newly acquired parachute and landed without injury.<ref name="obit" />

On 16 May 1929 Scholefield was killed when the aircraft crashed and burned at Shepperton on the shore of the [[River Thames]].<ref name="Times45205" /> Scholefield and his Mechanic S.W. Sherratt were test flying the [[Vickers Type 170 Vanguard|Vanguard]] airliner from [[Brooklands Aerodrome]] when control was lost and the aircraft nose-dived from 2000 feet into the ground.<ref name="Times45205" /> Observers had seen ''something fluttering away from the tail'' just before the aircraft dived.<ref name="Times45205" /> Scholefield was killed in the burnt wreck, and Sherratt who had jumped from the aircraft died from the fall.<ref name="Times45205" />

==Family life==
Scholefield had married Dorothy Seymour in 1919 and they had one  son in 1923.<ref name="obit" />

